Semilarski against the prosecutor&#39;s office: the cassation of the former vice-mayor of Tartu will be considered on August 4
This means that a decision on it is likely to be made in early September.
The courts of the two first instances refused to consider Semilarski&#39;s claim, but in April the State Court accepted his cassation appeal.
On December 12, 2019, the Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant, since its resolution is not within the competence of the administrative court.
The court ruling stated that the complaint contained a claim for compensation for damage caused in the course of criminal proceedings.
&quot;Such issues should be regulated by the prosecutor&#39;s office and the county court,&quot; Anette Kreitsmann, spokeswoman for the Tartu courts, told ERR earlier.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed this decision to the district court, which on February 5 did not change the decision of the court of first instance.
Now the State Court will have to say its word.
According to Semilarski&#39;s lawyer, attorney-at-law Oliver Nyaes, his client was unreasonably under suspicion of bribery for about two years.
Now he is demanding that the prosecutor&#39;s office refute the false allegations addressed to him and compensate him for moral damage.
The reason for filing a complaint with the court was the statements of the prosecutor for special cases of the Luna District Prosecutor&#39;s Office Margus Gross, made by him in October 2017, when Semilarski, along with another vice-mayor of Tartu at that time, Artem Suvorov, was detained on suspicion of committing several crimes.
&quot;Let us remind you that when I was detained, the Security Police and the Prosecutor&#39;s Office immediately organized a press conference and informed the entire Republic of Estonia that the leaders of Tartu - one of the most influential local governments - are corrupt.
These public suspicions hung in the air accompanied me for about two years.
And now, when these allegations and suspicions turned out to be false, the prosecutor&#39;s office does not want to say anything about it,&quot; Semilarski commented in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Näes, at the press conference the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework within which the prosecutor&#39;s office should operate.
&quot;The allegation of bribery and venality turned out to be false, but that&#39;s not the only issue here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia, as well as on Lithuania, that at the stage of investigation, state representatives should be careful in their choice of words so that suspects are not presented as criminals before sentencing.
The prosecutor&#39;s office is also obliged to do this by the presumption of innocence, which, unfortunately, was not respected in this case against Valvo Semilarski,&quot; Näes said.
&quot;Publicly presenting Semilarski as a serious offender and bribe-taker in circumstances where the facts underlying the suspicion of bribery are still emerging is unacceptable, contrary to the presumption of innocence and unfair to the complainant,&quot; the lawyer added.
As rus.err.ee wrote, Valvo Semilarski, the former deputy mayor of Tartu, will not be prosecuted on charges of bribery - the criminal case against him was partially closed in July.
At the same time, the former official is being tried on charges of deliberately violating anti-corruption laws when conducting transactions on an especially large scale.
According to the indictment, between 2015 and 2017, the former deputy mayor of Tartu participated more than thirty times in the meetings of the city government when making decisions related to companies operating in Tartu, with the owners or managers of which Semilarski actively communicated on a personal level outside of working hours.
According to Gross, in all these cases, Semilarski had personal interests, and therefore he had to step back from participating in decision-making.
Earlier, as rus.err.ee wrote, the prosecutor&#39;s office charged Semilarski with taking a bribe and violating anti-corruption laws when conducting transactions on an especially large scale.
This happened in October 2016, when he was detained along with another deputy mayor, Artem Suvorov (Centre Party).
At that time, the prosecutor&#39;s office and the Security Police stated that there was strong evidence against both vice-mayors.
After that, both officials resigned.
Suvorov&#39;s case later reached the court, which fully acquitted the politician.
The judicial investigation into the case of Valvo Semilarski is still ongoing.
