How will the decision of the Central Bank to reduce the key rate affect the economy
The Bank of Russia, as expected, lowered the key rate again.
It fell by another 0.25 percentage points, to 4.25% per annum - formally another historical low.
Judging by the return of the short rate cut step, as well as the tone of the Central Bank&#39;s statements and updated forecasts for the Russian economy, the regulator looks at the economic prospects more optimistic than before.
This means that the current cycle of monetary easing may soon come to a halt.
“We continued to ease monetary policy, primarily considering that there are still risks of inflation deviating downward from 4% in 2021,” said Elvira Nabiullina, head of the Bank of Russia.
They are associated with a significant decline in economic activity, a fall in domestic and external demand.
Economic recovery, according to Nabiullina, will take more than a year and a half.
At the same time, she noted that after the restrictions were lifted due to the pandemic, economic processes revived: energy consumption, consumer and investment demand recovered, construction and production of consumer goods expanded, and the annual rate of decline in transport freight turnover and industrial production slowed down.
According to the revised forecast of the Central Bank, in 2020 the contraction of the economy will be 4.5-5.5% (previously it was expected to be 4-6%), and the recovery growth of the economy in 2021 will be 3.5-4.5%, in 2022 - 2.5-3.5%.
In addition, the Bank of Russia revised its forecast for annual oil prices to $38 and $40 per barrel of Urals in 2020 and 2021, respectively.
Earlier, the Central Bank expected 27 and 35 dollars per barrel.
Finally, the Bank of Russia&#39;s inflation forecast for 2020 was 3.7-4.2% against the previously expected 3.8-4.8%.
The view of the Bank of Russia on the situation in the economy is becoming more optimistic, which brings us closer to the end of the easing cycle, say Sophia Donets and Andrey Melashchenko, economists for Russia and the CIS at Renaissance Capital.
Thus, the Bank of Russia has been consistently reducing the key rate for more than a year, since the beginning of last summer it has already fallen by 3.5 percentage points.
And at the last meeting in June, the Central Bank lowered it immediately by one percentage point due to low inflation due to suppressed demand and the need to stimulate the economy, which has slowed down due to the pandemic and related restrictions.
There are still chances to fine-tune monetary policy (at the next meeting on September 18 and before the end of the year), but the limit is already close, agrees Evgeny Koshelev, chief analyst at Rosbank.
The combination of pro-inflationary risks also points to the nearness of a pause in interest rate easing - disrupted supply chains, possible rising costs due to epidemic prevention measures and a faster (compared to expectations) recovery in demand, he says.
To top it off, the subsequent actions of the Bank of Russia will require more attention to inflationary processes during the harvest season, as well as external volatility, which has increased against the backdrop of geopolitical conflicts, Koshelev points out.
One way or another, the reduction in the key rate will lead to a further reduction in rates for the most reliable borrowers, and possibly also for mortgages, says Maxim Petronevich, senior economist at the analytical department of Otkritie Bank.
The rate correction will be less pronounced than the key rate cut, he said.
Interest rates on consumer loans may fall by another 0.3-0.6 percentage points during the second half of the year, mortgage rates may end the year in the range of 6.2-7%, BCS Premier economist Anton Pokatovich does not exclude.
Average deposit rates, in his opinion, will also fall - in the coming months they may drop to 4.2-4.5% (now barely above 4.5%).
Further, they may drop to 4% if the Central Bank lowers the key rate in the fall, Pokatovich believes.
